}
```
The new code we added inside "FlushKeylogBuffer" function will first lock the mutex to ensure thread safety. It will then assign the current log length (i) to the "length" parameter, which is used to return the length of data. Afterward, it allocates a specific amount of memory for the new buffer, then copies the current log in the "KeylogBuffer" to the new buffer. After copying, the portion of "KeylogBuffer" that contained the log will be cleared by setting its content to zero. Finally, the logging length (i) is reset to zero and the new buffer is returned.

